56	VIDEO CONTENT FILTERING OF EXPLICIT CONTENT USING 3D RESNET AND BILSTM ALGORITHM	The rapid proliferation of digital media has increased concerns about the exposure of individuals, particularly children, to inappropriate content. To address this issue, this study proposes the development of a Video Content Filtering System Using ResNet and BiLSTM Algorithm. The system is designed to detect and filter explicit content, specifically profanity in audio and kissing scenes in video, ensuring a safer viewing experience for users. The audio filtering module utilizes Bidirectional Long Short-Term Memory (BiLSTM) and Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers (BERT) to identify profane words from speech. The system employs speech recognition technology to convert spoken words into text, which is then processed to detect offensive language. vi Once detected, the explicit segments are bleeped to prevent inappropriate audio content from being heard. The video filtering module integrates 3D ResNet-18, a pre-trained deep learning model, to analyze video frames and identify kissing scenes. The detected explicit frames are blurred, ensuring that inappropriate visual content is obscured while maintaining the natural flow of the video. To evaluate the system’s performance, accuracy and F1-score were used as key metrics. The results demonstrate that the BiLSTM + BERT model for profanity detection achieves high accuracy in identifying explicit words, while the 3D ResNet-18 model effectively detects and blurs kissing scenes. The system was also assessed using ISO 25010 software quality standards, ensuring functionality, usability, and performance efficiency. The profanity detection component demonstrated strong performance achieving an accuracy of 90% and a F1-score of 90%, while the kissing detection component achieved promising results, achieving an accuracy of 79% and a F1-score of 84%. These findings suggest effective capabilities in automated video content moderation for explicit content. The researchers concludes that the developed system provides an effective and automated solution for filtering explicit content in videos. Future enhancements may include multilingual support for profanity detection and improved contextual understanding of explicit content.	BSCS
57	ARtified Galleries: Unleashing Art Appreciation Through Augmented Realit	This study developed ARtified, a mobile application designed to enhance art appreciation by integrating Augmented Reality and Convolutional Neural Networks in traditional gallery settings. It addresses the lack of interactivity and contextual engagement in conventional art displays, particularly among younger, tech-oriented audiences. The system utilizes CNNs for accurate image recognition and overlays multimedia content—text, audio, and images—onto physical artworks through AR technology. Developed using the Agile methodology, the project underwent iterative stages including planning, design, implementation, and testing. The application was evaluated through both qualitative and quantitative methods to determine its performance, usability, and overall effectiveness. Results demonstrated that the system significantly improved user engagement and understanding of artworks by delivering real-time contextual information. Based on the ISO 25010 Quality Standards, expert evaluations yielded strong agreement on the system’s functionality, usability, and efficiency. Additionally, user feedback confirmed that the application successfully delivered an enhanced interactive v gallery experience. The findings affirm the system’s ability to modernize traditional art appreciation by merging cultural content with emerging technology. For future research, it is recommended to expand the application’s capabilities through multi-language support and an extended artwork database to further increase accessibility and enrich the user experience across diverse audiences	BSCS
58	AbTech: A Rescue App for Instantaneous Emergency Response and First Aid Station Connectivity using Dijkstra’s Algorithm	Road traffic accidents are a leading cause of fatalities and injuries worldwide, often worsened by delayed emergency responses. This study introduces an automated accident detection and alert system using smartphones to reduce response times and casualties. The system monitors speed and location data to detect sudden changes indicative of a crash and triggers alerts to the nearest responders using Dijkstra’s algorithm for optimal routing. Dijkstra’s algorithm is used to find the fastest way to get help to the accident site. It works by creating a map where places like the accident location, hospitals, and responder stations are shown as points (called nodes), and the roads between them are lines (called edges) with travel times. The algorithm then finds the shortest route from the accident location to the nearest responder. Evaluations under ISO 25010 standards yielded a high overall score of 4.7, highlighting strong performance in functionality, efficiency, reliability, and usability. The system effectively improves emergency response times and enhances road safety by ensuring responders take the most efficient routes	BSCS
59	TeachAR: An Interactive Learning Mobile Application Using Convolutional Neural Network	The COVID-19 pandemic profoundly disrupted early childhood education, shifting learning from traditional face-to-face instruction to modular and online formats. While students gradually adapted, this transition exacerbated concerns about short attention spans and hyperactivity among young learners. Returning to in-person classes further highlighted these challenges, as teachers struggled to re-engage students accustomed to self-directed, screen-based learning. In response to these issues, this study introduces TeachAR, an interactive learning mobile application that leverages Augmented Reality (AR) and Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) to enhance early childhood education. The development of TeachAR followed the Throw-away Prototyping SDLC model, which allowed the development team to quickly create a working prototype to gather user feedback and refine the system's functionality and user interface. This iterative approach was instrumental in addressing usability concerns and aligning the application with the needs of its young target users, as well as the expectations of educators and guardians. iv For the intelligent object recognition feature, the YOLO (You Only Look Once) algorithm—specifically the YOLOv5 architecture—was implemented using Python, with deep learning frameworks such as PyTorch to support CNN-based training and real-time educational object detection. These technologies enabled the accurate classification of key learning elements such as letters, numbers, and shapes, which are crucial in early education. The system achieves its objectives, with an end evaluation resulting in an overall mean score of 4.6, indicating that the system meets a very high-quality standard according to ISO 25010 International Standards. This underscores TeachAR’s excellent quality and suitability for practical use, affirming its potential to address the attention and engagement challenges faced by young learners in the post-pandemic educational landscape.	BSCS
60	Enhancing Resume Screening Efficiency on Mobile Platforms through Parsing and Ranking Algorithm	In today’s digital and fast-paced hiring environment, traditional manual resume screening methods have become inefficient, time-consuming, and prone to human bias. This study proposes the development of a Resume Screening System, implemented as a mobile-responsive website, aimed at enhancing the efficiency, fairness, and objectivity of the applicant evaluation process. The system leverages parsing algorithms to extract structured data from PDF resumes and employs Latent Semantic Analysis (LSA)—a Natural Language Processing (NLP) technique—to assess the semantic relevance between applicant qualifications and job requirements. Through similarity scoring and ranking mechanisms, the system evaluates resumes based on education, skills, and experience, producing a prioritized list of candidates aligned with predefined job-specific metrics. Designed to streamline the hiring process for both employers and applicants, the platform supports job creation, resume submission, and applicant ranking in a user friendly and efficient manner. The system underwent evaluation using the ISO 25010 quality model, achieving a high overall mean score of 4.66, which indicates compliance with international software quality standards in areas such as functionality, performance, iv usability, maintainability, and security. The results demonstrate that the proposed system effectively automates and optimizes resume screening on mobile platforms, making it a practical tool for businesses and organizations seeking a smarter, technology-driven recruitment solution	BSCS
61	VIRTUAL PRIVATE NETWORK (VPN) FOR HOME NETWORK CONNECTION AND REMOTE FILE SHARING USING WIREGUARD PROTOCOL	The Virtual Private Network For Home Network Connection And File Sharing research project presents a system developed by using the Wireguard Protocol to create a virtual private network where devices could route all traffic through a designated egress point and share files among the devices. By employing the NAT Traversal, Port Forwarding and Wireguard Protocols, the system addresses problems in the Philippine Internet Service landscape such as data insecurity, limited and expensive internet and data plans. The system proposes a compelling alternative. A VPN tunnel is established and uses the user's home network to create a secure, encrypted tunnel. Remote users would be able to connect and effectively extend the home network to their location and routing all 5 their internet traffic through the home internet connection and allowing them to access their fil es remotely. This system was evaluated using ISO 25010 software quality standards, focusing on functionality, performance, usability, reliability, and security. Results indicate compliance with international standards, achieving an overall rating of "Good" with exceptional performance efficiency and compatibility. Key features include dynamic timetable creation, conflict resolution, and real-time updates within an intuitive interface, ensuring scalability and adaptability to varying institutional needs. The research contributes significantly to small-scale software defined networking by providing an effective, secure and economical solution that implements minimal configuration. This solution enhances the standard Filipino home-work/school network and establishes a foundation for future enhancements, such as completely minimizing the internet consumption from the remote device, developing a private individual coordinated server and availability to multiple platforms.	BSCS
62	Dynamic Image Protection: A Web-Based Script Against AI Scraping and Unauthorized Downloads	The widespread adoption of digital content-sharing platforms has increased the risks of unauthorized image use, particularly through AI-driven web scraping. Traditional security measures such as watermarking, JavaScript-based restrictions, and legal enforcement have proven insufficient in preventing the extraction and misuse of online images. Unauthorized image use presents significant disadvantages for content creators, including loss of intellectual property control, diminished revenue opportunities, and dilution of brand value. AI-powered scraping tools can bypass conventional protections, automatically collecting and processing vast amounts of visual data without creator consent. This study introduces the Dynamic Image Protection Script (DIPS), a web-based framework designed to safeguard images through multi-layered security mechanisms. DIPS integrates chaotic encryption using a Logistic Map XOR algorithm, JavaScript based client-side protections (right-click prevention, screenshot blocking), and server side AI-aware detection (rate limiting, behavioral fingerprinting). Testing demonstrated robust performance, with 94% accuracy in encryption/decryption, 92% effectiveness in blocking AI scrapers, and high user satisfaction ratings	BSCS
63	ILOCATE: A WEB-BASED BOARDING HOUSE FINDER IN ILOILO CITY USING THE HAVERSINE ALGORITHM	Finding suitable boarding houses remains a common challenge for students and workers relocating to Iloilo City due to limited availability, lack of advertisement, and outdated digital platforms. To address this issue, this study developed ILOcate: A Web- based Boarding House Finder in Iloilo City that helps tenants locate affordable, verified accommodations near their desired location. The system utilizes the Haversine Algorithm to calculate accurate distances between user and boarding house coordinates and integrates Google Maps API to provide real-time geospatial mapping and navigation. The application allows landlords to register their properties, including business permit verification, pricing, amenities, photos, and exact GPS location. It also includes administrative features enabling the Iloilo Boarding House Commission to monitor, verify, or close listings, and tenants to file complaints. The system's effectiveness was evaluated using the ISO 25010 software quality model, yielding an overall mean rating of 4.5 (Excellent), while user acceptability testing resulted in a 4.68 overall mean (Excellent), highlighting strong functionality, usability, and performance efficiency. ILOcate serves as a comprehensive digital solution that enhances transparency, accessibility, and user experience in boarding house selection—bridging the gap between tenants and landlords in Iloilo City through reliable map-based services.	BSCS
64	School Timetable Generator	The School Timetable Generator research project presents a system developed using Google Sheets and Google Apps Script to automate the scheduling of academic timetables for teachers, sections, and rooms. By employing the First Fit Decreasing (FFD) and Constraint Satisfaction Programming (CSP) algorithms, the system addresses complex scheduling constraints, including teacher availability, room capacity, and subject time sensitivity, while optimizing the allocation of resources. The tool generates conflict- free schedules efficiently, reducing the manual workload and ensuring adherence to academic requirements. This system was evaluated using ISO 25010 software quality standards, focusing on functionality, performance, usability, reliability, and security. Results indicate compliance with international standards, achieving an overall rating of "Good" with exceptional performance efficiency and compatibility. Key features include dynamic timetable creation, conflict resolution, and real-time updates within an intuitive interface, ensuring scalability and adaptability to varying institutional needs. The research contributes significantly to academic scheduling by providing an efficient, automated solution that minimizes errors, enhances satisfaction among v educators and administrators, and establishes a foundation for future enhancements, such as part-time scheduling and backtracking capabilities.	BSCS
