entered solution for self-service printing in academic environment	BSIT
79	Fish Catch Landing Monitoring System	Fishing remains a crucial source of livelihood and food security in the Philippines; however, the Department of Agriculture’s (DA) continued reliance on manual paper-based systems has resulted in inefficiencies, data inaccuracies, and limited access torealtime information. These limitations hinder timely decision-making and effective fisherymanagement. Thus, this study aimed to develop a fish-catch monitoring systemthat records a fisherman’s daily catch. This system allows fish enumerators to digitallyinput essential information, including species, size, weight, and landing locations, via mobiledevices. Key features include real-time data validation, centralized cloud storage, andautomated report generation with outputs categorized by species and geographicdistribution. The evaluation was based on the ISO/IEC 25010 software quality model andfocused on functionality, usability, reliability, and efficiency. Results reveal anoverall mean score of 4.1, described as “Very Good,” demonstrating the systemhas significantlyimproved data accuracy, accessibility, and transparency. In addition, the digital transformation of the fish catch landing and monitoring system enhances operational efficiency and ensures timely access to data. By providing accurate and visualizeddata, DA and other stakeholders can make informed decisions and respond proactivelytochanges in fish stocks and market demand.	BSIT
80	THE DEVELOPMENT OF “PRODUCTLOCA”: A PRODUCT FINDER SYSTEM	The development of “ProductLoca”: A Product Finder System resulted in a portal-type system designed to allocate and manage products, business information, store details, floor plans, kiosk device locations, and generate a list of frequently searched products. This study aims to address the inefficient and time-consuming process that customers face when locating products. The system, developed using PHP and MySQL, enables super administrators and administrators to manage and analyze product search data, configure store information, and potentially oversee user accounts. It also enables customers to quickly and easily locate products within the store through a search functionality, access detailed product information, and utilize store mapping features for efficient navigation. The system was evaluated based on ISO 25010 standards, including functionality, reliability, usability, efficiency, security, compatibility, maintainability, and portability. The researchers used purposive sampling to recruit respondents, including twenty (20) shoppers, ten (10) students, ten (10) mall employees, and four (4) information and communication technology (ICT) experts who were also store managers. iv These ICT experts, comprising development specialists, IT professionals, and professors, evaluated the system using the eight ISO quality standards. The evaluation results indicated that “ProductLoca”: A Product Finder System met the study’s objectives and performed effectively, achieving an overall rating of 4.35 (Very Satisfactory). Functional Suitability was rated 4.43 (Very Satisfactory), Performance Efficiency 4.41 (Very Satisfactory), Compatibility 4.37 (Very Satisfactory), Usability 4.49 (Very Satisfactory), Reliability 4.37 (Very Satisfactory), Maintainability 4.15 (Satisfactory), and Portability 4.32 (Very Satisfactory).	BSIT
81	SMART TRANSIT: REAL-TIME MODERNIZED JEEPNEY TRACKING FOR PASSENGERS	A reliable transportation system is essential for reducing traffic congestion, which is a common problem in Iloilo City. By offering efficient public transport, which helps ease road traffic and makes daily commuting more convenient. With the use of advanced technologies like GPS tracking [1], modernized jeepneys have become easier to monitor in real time. This is especially helpful for students and daily commuters who often experience long waits and uncertainty about bus arrivals. Despite the improvements, many commuters still face delays, causing stress and inconvenience. To help solve this problem, this study developed a system called Smart Transit: Real-Time Modernized Jeepney Tracking for Passengers. The system includes real-time jeepney tracking and a location-pinning feature that lets passengers mark where they want to be picked up. This helps conductors and operators respond more efficiently. The project was carried out at Iloilo Science and Technology University (ISAT U) Iloilo City Campus and followed the Agile Software Development Model. The system was tested and evaluated using the ISO 25010 standard for software quality and participants were chosen through purposive sampling. The results showed that the system met its goals and performed excellently in terms of functionality, ease of use and overall effectiveness.	BSIT
82	Private Community Security System: Car Visitor Tracking using GIS and GPS	Private subdivisions and gated communities commonly rely on traditional security measures such as manual logbooks, CCTV surveillance, and gate personnel to monitor incoming vehicles. While these tools provide basic monitoring, they are prone to human error, data inconsistency, and a lack of real-time response, making it difficult to efficiently verify and manage visitor access. These limitations can lead to gaps in security, increased workload for personnel, and delayed responses during peak hours or emergencies. There is a growing need for integrated, automated security systems that improve accuracy, accountability, and real-time monitoring. This study developed the Private Community Security System: Car Visitor Tracking using GIS and GPS, an innovative solution that integrates Geographic Information System (GIS) mapping, Global Positioning System (GPS) tracking, and biometric fingerprint verification. The system uses a fingerprint-secured GPS tracker attached to each visitor’s vehicle, which transmits live location data to a web-based dashboard. This allows security personnel to monitor visitor vehicles in real-time while ensuring the integrity and identity of each visitor through biometric verification. Additionally, the system records historical movement data for auditing and incident analysis. To evaluate the system’s performance, the study employed the ISO 25010 software quality model, gathering feedback from 19 participants, including IT professionals, security guards, and general users. Key metrics included functional suitability, usability, performance efficiency, maintainability, and portability. The results indicated an overall Excellent rating, validating the system's effectiveness in improving visitor management. Minor areas for improvement included compatibility and reliability, which did not significantly impact the system’s performance. This research demonstrates that integrating tracking, authentication, and real-time monitoring provides a robust, scalable solution to modernize security operations in gated communities. The system offers enhanced visibility, faster response times, and improved control over vehicle entry, making it a valuable tool for private community safety	BSIT
84	“U-Sync: Unifying Event System”	In educational institutions and multi-department organizations, managing events effectively is a recurring challenge due to fragmented communication channels and inconsistent scheduling practices. Events are often announced separately through various departmental social media platforms, resulting in redundancy, missed opportunities, and poor coordination. To address this issue, U-Sync: Unifying Events System was developed as a comprehensive web and mobile application that centralizes event management. The system introduces a structured, role-based framework with distinct user roles Administrators, Managers, and Viewers designed to streamline event coordination, enhance user engagement, and foster community collaboration. Key features include dynamic calendar generation, role and permission management, email push notifications, OTP-based authentication for secure access, and subscription-enabled administrative tools. U-Sync’s performance was evaluated using the ISO 25010 software quality standards, which assess nine critical dimensions: Functional Suitability, Performance Efficiency, Compatibility, Usability, Reliability, Security, Maintainability, Flexibility, and Safety. Results indicated an overall “Excellent” rating, with Safety achieving the highest score, while Reliability was identified as an area for further improvement. In conclusion, U-Sync demonstrates significant potential in improving information dissemination and event management within institutional settings. It lays a strong foundation for unified communication and efficient planning. Future enhancements are recommended to focus on increasing system dependability, scalability, user engagement, and expanding the scope of real-time notification features.	BSIT
85	VIRTUEBANWA: A GAMIFIED INSTRUCTIONAL MATERIAL FOR GMRC	The traditional education system faces persistent challenges such as limited personalization, rigid curricula, and insufficient student engagement, particularly in values education. In response, this study introduces VirtueBanwa, a gamified instructional material designed to enhance the teaching and learning experience of Good Manners and Right Conduct (GMRC) among Grade 1 students in Iloilo. Anchored on the Department of Education’s MATATAG Curriculum and Republic Act No. 11476, which mandates GMRC as a core subject, the project leverages gamification to deliver moral and ethical lessons in an interactive, student-centered manner. Using a system prototyping methodology, the 2D mobile game was developed with Unity and C#, integrating simulations, visual and audio elements, and core gameplay mechanics aligned with the Most Essential Learning Competencies (MELCs) of GMRC. The system includes features for managing student and classroom data, delivering lessons through play, and tracking and updating student progress. Its effectiveness was evaluated using ISO 25010 standards through purposive sampling of five teachers, and five IT practitioners from a rural school in Iloilo. Results indicate an overall "Excellent" rating (4.26 on the Likert Scale), demonstrating the system’s success in fostering engagement, improving retention of moral values, and supporting the holistic development of learners through innovative educational technology.	BSIT
86	CROWDRELIEF: EMPOWERING DISASTER RELIEF THROUGH CROWDFUNDING INNOVATION	CrowdRelief is a web-based crowdfunding platform designed to improve disaster relief by tackling inefficiencies in resource distribution, stakeholder coordination, and donation transparency. It aims to streamline relief efforts, promoting better coordination, resource use, and trust in donation processes. The platform facilitates the launch, management, and donation of disaster relief campaigns, catering primarily to donors and fundraisers through various donation types including monetary and in-kind contributions. The platform’s development followed an iterative prototyping methodology. Interviews were conducted to gather requirements from non-governmental organizations, local government units, and individual donors. The platform was built using PHP and MySQL, incorporating secure user authentication, real-time donation tracking, and an intuitive interface for stakeholder interaction. Alpha and beta testing phases, incorporating stakeholder feedback, enabled iterative refinements to ensure the platform’s usability and alignment with disaster relief operational requirements. The software's quality was evaluated by a panel comprising three (3) IT experts, one (1) NGO representative, two (2) LGU representatives, and fifty (50) random donors, utilizing the ISO/IEC 25010 standard. The assessment yielded an overall "Very Satisfactory" rating, with specific scores as follows: Functional Suitability (4.39), Performance Efficiency (4.11), Compatibility (4.29), Usability (4.28), Reliability (4.25), Security (4.25), Maintainability (4.23), and Portability (4.26). These findings substantiate the platform's efficacy, stability, and suitability for operational deployment. CrowdRelief provides a scalable solution that addresses transparency and coordination gaps in existing disaster relief systems, offering potential for broader crisis response applications and advancing disaster management practices.	BSIT
87	"Solis Tabula Vestigator: An Automated Solar Tracking and Monitoring System"	In recent years, the global transition toward sustainable energy has emphasized the need for innovative solutions to maximize the efficiency of renewable resources, particularly solar power. Solar energy is abundant and clean, but its efficiency largely depends on how effectively a solar panel can capture sunlight. Traditional fixed-position panels are limited by their static orientation, leading to suboptimal energy collection as the sun moves across the sky, resulting in reduced energy efficiency. To address this, the study developed the Solis Tabula Vestigator, an automated solar tracking and monitoring system designed to optimize energy collection through dynamic panel adjustment and real-time performance tracking. The system features a solar tracking device capable of both rotation and tilting, allowing it to align with the sun more effectively throughout the day. A custombuilt web application complements the device by enabling users to remotely monitor sensor data, compare energy performance between automated and static systems on both daily and hourly bases, and export data as CSV reports for further analysis. Results from daily and hourly comparisons show that the automated system consistently harvested more energy than the static panel. The user interface provided intuitive visualizations and access to energy reports and sensor readings, and data exports for in-depth analysis. To ensure quality, the system was evaluated using the ISO/IEC 25010 framework, which assessed nine software quality characteristics: functional suitability, performance efficiency, compatibility, interaction capability, reliability, security, maintainability, flexibility, and safety. The system received an overall excellent rating of 4.13. In conclusion, the Solis Tabula Vestigator successfully achieved its development objectives and proved to be an efficient, reliable, and user-friendly solution for enhancing solar energy utilization through automated tracking and real-time performance monitoring.	BSIT
88	SOWSMART: AUTOMATED FEEDER FOR HOG RAISERS	This study aimed to develop SowSmart: Automated Feeder for Hog Raisers, a system that addresses the challenges faced by hog raisers in efficiently managing feeding schedules for their livestock. One of the common problems of hog raisers is the inconsistency in feeding times and portioning, which affects the health and growth of their hogs. The system focuses on automating feeding schedules, tracking hog metrics, and maintaining detailed feeding records to ensure optimal livestock management. The application enables users to oversee pig pens, monitor individual hogs, and schedule feedings seamlessly. The system's features also include the ability to track hog metrics, automate feeding processes, and improve management efficiency through its intuitive interface. SowSmart was tested using End-to-End and White Box Testing methods. These methodologies ensured that the system performed flawlessly both functionally and structurally. Respondents evaluated the system using the ISO 25010 standard and rated it as “Excellent.”	BSIT
89	Customized 3D Fashion Design and Order Management System	This study aimed to develop a customized 3D fashion design and order management system that integrates effective order management with advanced 3D modeling, offering a relevant and innovative solution for the modern fashion industry. This study addresses the shortcomings of traditional fashion design processes, which are often characterized by inefficiencies, limited personalization, and a lack of real-time visualization. Using a customized 3D fashion design and order management system enables users to create customized clothing by selecting fabric types, colors, and design features through real-time 3D modeling. The system offers seamless order management functionalities, including customer chat support, order monitoring dashboards, automated billing statement generation, and real-time notification updates. The system was evaluated based on the ISO 25010 software quality model and rated on eight prominent characteristics: functional suitability, performance efficiency, compatibility, usability, reliability, security, maintainability, and portability. Evaluation findings, collated from diverse respondents such as IT professionals, business managers, employees, and students, depicted satisfactory performance in all the quality characteristics. The result revealed an overall mean score of 3.79, described as “Very Satisfactory”. The Customized 3D Fashion Design and Order Management System, successfully bridges the gap between digital fashion design and practical manufacturing processes. It offers a sustainable, efficient, and user-friendly platform that meets modern industry demands while providing customers with greater control and personalization in their fashion choices. The positive evaluation outcomes validate the system's potential for real-world application and future expansion in the digital fashion marketplace.	BSIT
90	SERVICE CONNECT IT: REQUEST AND SUPPORT SYSTEM	The Service Connect IT: Request and Support System is a system that aims to digitalize service requests made by the users. The MIS department, however, is still using the traditional method of taking requests in a paper-based form, which result in the requests that going missing, and getting delayed. The system provides a user with an easy and convenient way of processing their request which is through an automated request form that is made possible with the system named Service Connect IT: Request and Support System. The user, specifically the Faculty/Staff can start initiating their request through filling up the necessary items in submitting the request. Technical Staff will then be the one to process the requests made by the faculty/staff until they become resolved. Finally, the MIS Staff will be responsible for accepting or declining requests, providing prioritization, managing the user’s account, and tracking the request history. The Service Connect IT: Request and Support System was tested using white box testing by IT experts based on the International Organization of Standardization (ISO 25010). The Reliability received the highest rating based on ISO 25010 quality standards with the (M=4.7, SD=0.10). This result implies that the overall Reliability of The system is “Excellent” in terms of Reliability. This concludes that the system meets the specified conditions and covers all the specified tasks and user objectives characterized by ISO 25010.	BSIT
91	ISAT U MEDICAL CLINIC MANAGEMENT SYSTEM WITH CHATBOT	The study aimed to design and develop the ISAT-U Medical Clinic Management System with Chatbot to improve the management of patient information, symptom assessment, appointment scheduling, SMS notifications, and the generation of initial diagnoses. The system was also evaluated based on the ISO/IEC 25010 software quality standards, which include functional suitability, stability, reliability, usability, performance efficiency, security, compatibility, maintainability, and portability. To assess the system’s effectiveness, the researchers used purposive and convenience sampling techniques, selecting a total of 25 respondents 21 Information Technology students and 4 IT experts who had relevant knowledge about the system. The findings showed that the system met all its intended objectives. Specifically, Functional Stability received the highest rating of 4.29, followed by Compatibility with 4.21, Usability with 4.17, Security and Performance Efficiency both at 4.10, and Portability with 4.08. All criteria were rated as “Very Satisfactory,” indicating that the system is functional, secure, and user-friendly. Although the results were highly positive, the evaluation also highlighted opportunities for further enhancement, particularly in optimizing performance and improving system portability. Overall, the system has proven to be an effective, efficient, and scalable solution for modernizing healthcare services within the university	BSIT
92	LEAFLENS: DEVELOPMENT OF MOBILE APPLICATION USING IMAGE ANALYSIS FOR OPTIMAL RICE HARVESTING AND FERTILIZATION	Rice farming remains an essential component of food security in the Philippines. Despite technological advancements, many local farmers continue to assess nitrogen levels in rice crops manually by relying on the Leaf Color Chart (LCC), a traditional tool for determining leaf health based on color. While widely used, this method is subjective and prone to inaccuracies, as it heavily depends on human perception and environmental conditions. The primary problem identified in this study is the inefficiency and unreliability of manual leaf color assessment, which often leads to improper fertilizer application. This v may result in either nutrient deficiency or over-fertilization, negatively affecting crop yield. To address this issue, the researchers developed LeafLens, a mobile application designed to assist farmers in evaluating the nitrogen status of rice leaves through image analysis. The application utilizes a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN), specifically the MobileNetV2 architecture, to classify rice leaf colors accurately and provide data-driven recommendations regarding fertilizer application and optimal harvest timing. The findings of the study indicate that LeafLens achieved high accuracy in classifying leaf color. The application successfully delivered appropriate fertilizer suggestions and harvest period estimates. These results demonstrate the potential of LeafLens to support precision farming and contribute to sustainable agricultural practices.	BSIT
93	SKOLAR KONEK: ISAT U Scholarship Application and Ranking System	The increasing demand for scholarships at Iloilo Science and Technology University (ISAT U) has highlighted the limitations of manual, fragmented scholarship application processes. Students often face challenges in accessing information, applying efficiently, and tracking the status of their applications. To address these issues, the researchers developed "SKOLAR KONEK: ISAT U Scholarship Application and Ranking System", a web-based platform that simplifies and digitizes the entire scholarship management process. The system enables students to register, apply, and receive recommendations for scholarships, while sponsors can post opportunities, review applications, and automatically generate applicant rankings based on predefined criteria. The system was developed using the prototyping methodology, which involved iterative phases of planning, analysis, design, testing, and refinement. It incorporates automated functions such as document submission, eligibility filtering, and real-time status tracking. ISO 25010 software quality standards were applied for evaluation, with results from IT experts and student users indicating excellent ratings across usability, functionality, performance, and security.	BSIT
94	SILENT VOICE: FILIPINO SIGN LANGUAGE TRANSLATOR SOFTWARE	Hearing loss affects over 1.7 million individuals in the Philippines, creating significant communication barriers between the deaf and hearing communities. Filipino Sign Language (FSL) is the primary language of the deaf, yet many hearing individuals lack the proficiency to communicate, leading to challenges in accessibility and inclusion. Existing sign language translation tools primarily support English and rely on static image recognition, failing to capture the real-time dynamic hand gestures used in natural conversations. This limitation restricts effective communication and excludes many Filipino deaf individuals from meaningful interactions. To address this issue, this study developed a web-based Filipino Sign Language Translator capable of recognizing and translating dynamic FSL gestures into words. The system employs a MediaPipe-Long Short-Term Memory hybrid model, where MediaPipe extracts real-time hand landmarks, and Long Short-Term Memory networks classify sequential hand gestures. The system’s accuracy was evaluated using the F1 Score, achieving a weighted average of 0.91, demonstrating high precision and reliability in gesture recognition. vi The study further assessed the system’s usability through the Technology Acceptance Model (TAM), focusing on Perceived Usefulness (PU) and Perceived Ease of Use (PEU). Results revealed overwhelmingly positive user acceptance, with PU scoring 4.54 and PEU scoring 4.43, both rated as “Very Satisfactory.” These findings indicate that users strongly affirmed the system’s effectiveness in recognizing and translating FSL gestures, while finding it intuitive, accessible, and practical for real-world use. This study successfully achieved its objectives, demonstrating that a real-time FSL translation system is not only viable but revolutionary in enhancing communication between the deaf and hearing communities. By offering real-time dynamic gesture recognition, this system marks a significant step towards a greater inclusivity and accessibility.	BSIT
95	DEVELOPMENT OF ENVIROLINK: A ENVIRONMENTAL CROWDSOURCING PLATFORM	The environmental engagement gap in the Philippines poses a significant challenge, limiting effective participation in sustainability initiatives and reducing community impact. The study, "Development of EnviroLink: An Environmental Crowdsourcing Platform," addresses this issue. It is a web-based platform that connects Campaign Managers, Volunteers, and Administrators through an automated campaign management system. EnviroLink enables Campaign Managers to create detailed campaign profiles including objectives and locations, while allowing Volunteers to join based on their interests and Administrators to oversee approvals. The system ensures efficient coordination by aligning campaign needs with volunteer capabilities using a structured process for campaign creation and submission. The system was developed using the Extreme Programming Agile Methodology. Campaign Managers, Volunteers, and IT experts evaluated it using ISO 25010 standards, achieving a "Very Satisfactory" rating (mean 4.50). The system enhances environmental participation, reduces administrative burdens, and improves campaign efficiency. This study provides a scalable solution to boost environmental engagement in the Philippines, with potential applications for future research and sustainability platforms.	BSIT
96	DEVELOPMENT OF IJOMA: A PORTAL-TYPE JOB-MATCHING SYSTEM	The job-skills mismatch in the Philippines poses a significant challenge, contributing to unemployment and underemployment by creating barriers to effective job placement. The study, "Development of IJOMA: A Portal-Type Job-Matching System", addresses this issue. It is a web-based platform that connects job seekers with employers through an automated job-matching recommendation system. IJOMA (I Job Match) enables job seekers to create detailed profiles including personal details, education, skills, and experience, while allowing employers to customize job postings with weighted criteria. The system ensures precise matching by aligning job seeker qualifications with employer requirements by utilizing advanced techniques such as Sentence-BERT, fuzzy logic, and a two-layer weighting process. The system was developed using the Extreme Programming Agile Methodology. Job seekers, employers, and IT experts evaluated it using ISO 25010 standards, achieving a "Very Satisfactory" rating (mean 4.26). The system improves recruitment, reduces mismatches, and enhances job search efficiency. This study provides a scalable solution to improve job matching in the Philippines, with potential applications for future research and recruitment platforms.	BSIT
97	PADAYON: A DEVELOPMENT OF AI APPLICATION FOR HILIGAYNON SPEAKERS WITH EMOTION RECOGNITION	Mental health remains a critical global concern, particularly for individuals facing emotional challenges who are further hindered by linguistic and cultural barriers in accessing professional care. In the Philippines, the lack of regionally inclusive mental health support systems poses challenges for Hiligaynon-speaking users. This study introduced Padayon, a web-based AI application designed to provide emotion-aware mental health support through culturally sensitive chatbot interactions. The system integrates Natural Language Processing (NLP) for text-based emotion recognition and vi DeepFace for facial expression analysis, enabling real-time detection of user emotions through both textual and visual inputs. The system was developed using the Extreme Programming (XP) methodology, emphasizing iterative development phases including planning, design, coding, and release. A purposive sampling technique was employed to select twenty (n = 20) respondents, comprising Hiligaynon speakers, IT professionals, students, and mental health practitioners. The system's software quality was evaluated using the ISO 25010 Software Quality Standards, covering eight quality characteristics. The emotion recognition model achieved a weighted average F1-Score of 0.86, indicating a high level of accuracy and consistency in detecting user emotions. While the overall software quality evaluation yielded an average mean score of 4.39, rated as “Very Satisfactory.” High scores in Security (M=4.75), Compatibility (M=4.60), and Flexibility (M=4.53) confirmed the application's robustness, adaptability, and secure performance. User feedback reflected positive reception in terms of usability, reliability, and emotional responsiveness Results indicated that Padayon effectively recognized user emotions, delivered contextually appropriate responses, and achieved high user satisfaction rates. Thus, this study demonstrates the potential of AI-driven solutions in enhancing emotional support services for underrepresented language groups, fostering emotional resilience and well-being through an innovative, user-centered approach.	BSIT
98	BUZZING BEE QUEST: A WEB - BASED PIXELADVENTURE	This study focuses on the design, development, and evaluation of BuzzingBeeQuest: A Web-Based Pixel Adventure, an educational game aimed at enhancingfourth-grade students’ engagement and performance in English, Science, and Math. The gameintegrates gamification and pixel art design to create a fun, interactive learningenvironment aligned with curriculum standards. Developed using web technologies and evaluated based on ISO25010 standards, the game was assessed across key software quality attributes, including Usability, Performance Efficiency, Compatibility, Reliability, Security, Maintainability, and vi Portability. Evaluation results indicated high user satisfaction, with averageratings interpreted as Excellent, particularly in Usability (4.35), Performance Efficiency(4.28), and Security (4.38). The game features random level generation, scoring systems, progress tracking, and curriculum-aligned challenges designed to support cognitive development andboost student motivation. The findings affirm the effectiveness of gamified learningtoolsinenhancing educational engagement and improving learning outcomes. Recommendations for future development include integrating reward systems, diverse playable characters, interactive maps, and level-based progression. This researchcontributes to the growing field of educational gamification, providing a dynamicplatform that fosters 21st-century learning skills in elementary education.	BSIT
99	“IoT – INTEGRATED AND DRIP IRRIGATION AND GROWTH MONITORING SYSTEM FOR TOMATO PLANT”	The IoT-Integrated Drip Irrigation and Growth Monitoring System for Tomato Plant is designed to improve crop productivity whether it is planted on or off season. Its primary goal is to develop a system that automates the water distribution and growth monitoring using IoT systems for greenhouse tomato crop. Diamante Max (Solanum lycopersicum.), locally known as kamatis is one of the most profitable crops for off season production preferably from May to September. However, farmers here in the Philippines currently do not invest in technological advancements that could help in the production and stick to traditional planting instead. Addressing this gap, the researchers develop a study specifically for off season farming that uses greenhouse farming. It has a system that can monitor the plant growth, detect soil moisture as well as soil macronutrient (NPK) and vi automates drip irrigation that can be beneficial for maximum production of tomato plants. It includes a custom web-based application that provides a user-friendly interface for monitoring real time updates from the sensors. It has added features where the user can receive notification and updates via email. It has an added feature wherein data can be exported to PDF and CSV file. The study was built using C++ for the microcontroller and javascript programming language for the software and followed Prototyping Model. The system was evaluated using ISO 25010 standards resulting in "Excellent" with an average rate of 4.80 as rated by one (1) General User, two (2) Agriculturist, three (3) Students, and four (4) IT Professional. This implies the overall excellence of the system in catering the needs of tomato plants demonstrating its potential as a reliable and effective solution for improving the production of tomato plants.	BSIT
100	GUPPY SHOW MANAGEMENT SYSTEM	The Guppy Show Management System is a web-based platform designed to streamline the process of managing and participating in events. The system provided a comprehensive solution for both organizers and contestants by offering tools for event creation, entry submission, and payment processing. This platform aimed to enhance user experience through a user-friendly interface that facilitates efficient event management. The system allowed event organizers to create and manage events, invite participants, and categorize entries. Contestants can upload their entries in multiple categories and process payments directly within the platform. Additionally, the system offered features to evaluate entries and interact with posted results through comments and likes, promoting engagement and feedback.	BSIT
101	SMARTPARK: REAL-TIME PARKING AVAILABILITYSYSTEM	The persistent challenge of inefficient parking management on universitycampuses frequently leads to frustration among drivers and a waste of their valuabletime. To address the specific parking difficulties encountered at Iloilo Science and TechnologyUniversity (ISAT U), this capstone project developed SmartPark, a web applicationdelivering real-time information regarding parking availability. By employing a systemsprototyping approach and utilizing Raspberry Pi devices for camera-driven detectionofparking space occupancy, SmartPark offers users an easily understandable, color-codedreal-time view of parking options and equips administrators with effective tools foroversight. Main functionalities of the system include a real-time display of the parkingmap, automated identification of occupied parking spaces, recording of parking duration, comprehensive administrative tools for users and parking areas, violation notifications, and report generation capabilities. Evaluated against the ISO 25010 standard usinginput from individuals associated with ISAT U, SmartPark achieved an overall "Excellent"rating (mean 4.40). This positive feedback indicates that SmartPark couldgreatlyenhance the parking experience at ISAT U. Future efforts should aimto make vehicledetection more accurate, improve the system's performance, add features that meet userneeds, and make the system more adaptable for different situations.	BSIT
102	Android Based Voting System	The Android Based Voting System was developed to be used in Iloilo Scienceand Technology University for the convenience of voters during the election. The systemis designed to help the voters to cast votes easily. The proposed systemis an androidapplication that uses fingerprint for authentication. The system can tally votes automatically, and the result cannot be manipulated by the administrator. The system users consists of the administrator who will be able to viewandupdate the information of all the candidates, partylist, organization, election and the voter’s information. The administrator will be the one to restore all the informationinthesystem storage. vi The system send an SMS notification containing their account and passwordbefore the election period. During this, the users will be need to log in to their mobiledevices to vote and the system will require their fingerprint to be scanned for verification. The system will automatically show the result after the election period and the user will receive another SMS notification for the final result of election. The researchers tested the system wherein the selected users will do an evaluation. The Android Based Voting System was tested using the black box and white box testingwhich tested all the quality requirements of the system. Purposive sampling was usedinthe selection of the respondents based on ISO 25010.	BSIT
103	SAILO: DEVELOPMENT OF TICKETING SYSTEM FOR POINT TO POINT FERRY BOAT TERMINALS	This study presents the development of Sailo: A Ticketing System for Point-toPoint Ferry Boat Terminals, a web-based and mobile version designed to automate and enhance the ferry ticketing process between Iloilo and Guimaras. Traditional ticketing methods result in long queues, limited payment options, and inefficient data management, leading to operational challenges for ferry operators. Sailo addresses these issues by enabling passengers to book tickets online, make secure payments using a digital credit system, and generate tickets with QR codes for smooth verification at terminals. The system also automates terminal management, booking transactions, passenger verification, report generation, and to evaluate based on ISO 25010 Quality Standards, ensuring its compliance with Functional Suitability, Reliability, Usability, Performance, Efficiency, Security, Compatibility, Maintainability, and Portability. The researchers used the purposive sampling technique to select respondents who have the knowledge about the system. There are twenty (20) composed of; Terminal Admin, Ticket Agent and Ferry Operators and fifty (50) Passengers for both Guimaras and Iloilo, and two (2) IT Experts who served as respondents of the system. The findings revealed that the system satisfied all the objectives that were mentioned above. The results of the evaluation show that the overall average score was 4.39. This rating falls under the category of "Excellent." This means that the system has successfully met the quality standards based on the ISO 25010 model. In other words, the system performs very well in terms of quality, and it meets the expectations for a high-quality software product. The high score indicates that users are very satisfied with the system’s features, functions, and overall performance.	BSIT
